Descriptive Statistics for Social Network¶

Network-Level Statistics¶

  • Size of a Social Network
    • number of links
  • Order of a Social Network
    • number of nodes
  • Diameter of Social Network
    • maximum of shortest path lengths
  • Average Path Length of a Social Network
    • mean of shortest path lengths
  • Density of a Social Network
    • fraction of possible links that are present
  • Giant Component Order of a Social Network
    • largest set of connected nodes
    • strongly connected component: set of nodes that can reach each other by directed links
    • weakly connected component: set of nodes connected somehow
network-level statistics
size order diameter average_path_length density giant
31 10 5 2.155556 0.3444444 10

Node-Level Statistics¶

  • Shortest Path Length between a Pair of Nodes
    • smallest number of links that connect a pair of nodes
  • Indegree of a Node
    • number of distinct links from a node
    • calculate: sum columns of adjacency matrix
  • Outdegree of a Node
    • number of distinct links to a node
    • calculate: sum rows of adjacency matrix
  • Betweenness of a Node
    • the "Power Broker" can block dissemination of information
    • tendency of node to reside on shortest paths
    • number of shortest paths between any two nodes that include this node
  • Average Path Length of a Node
    • mean of shortest path lengths between this node and any other node
  • Closeness of a Node
    • the "Disseminator" can quickly disseminate information
    • inverse of average shortest path length
  • Eccentricity of a Node
    • the "Outcast" may have little communicationm with most other nodes
    • shortest path length to farthest other node
  • Eigencentrality of a Node
    • the "Influencer"
    • a node with high eigencentrality is connected to many nodes which themselves have high eigencentrality
    • technically: the values of first eigenvector of the adjacency matrix
    • PageRank is a variant of eigencentrality

PageRank without Dampening¶

Approximates the probability of arriving at a node by randomly following many links.

Algorithm¶

Here is the algorithm to calculate the pageranks of nodes in a social network:

  • For each node, initialize a pagerank. The pageranks can be equal or different from each other, but sum to one.
  • Repeat several times ...
    • For each node, revise its pagerank to be the weighted sum of pageranks contributed by all nodes that link to it. The weight that goes with a certain node's contribution is based on how many links emit from that node.


Here is the calculation to revise a pagerank:

$ pagerank_i \leftarrow \sum_{j \, \in \, C(i)} \frac{pagerank_j}{L(j)} $

where ...

  • $pagerank_i$ is the pagerank of the $i^{th}$ node
  • $pagerank_j$ is the pagerank of the $j^{th}$ node
  • $C(i)$ is the set of nodes that link to the $i^{th}$ node
  • $L(j)$ is the outdegree of the $j^{th}$ node
  • $N$ is the number of nodes (order)

PageRank with Dampening¶

Approximates the probability of arriving at a node by randomly following links occasionally transporting to a new node.

Algorithm¶

Here is the algorithm to calculate the pageranks of nodes in a social network:

  • For each node, initialize a pagerank. The pageranks can be equal or different from each other, but sum to one.
  • Repeat several times ...
    • For each node, revise its pagerank to be the weighted sum of pageranks contributed by all nodes that link to it. The weight that goes with a certain node's contribution is based on how many links emit from that node.


Here is the calculation to revise a pagerank:

$ pagerank_i \leftarrow d \big( \sum_{j \, \in \, C(i)} \frac{pagerank_j}{L(j)} \big) + \frac{1-d}{N} $

where ...

  • $pagerank_i$ is the pagerank of the $i^{th}$ node
  • $pagerank_j$ is the pagerank of the $j^{th}$ node
  • $d$ is a dampening factor ($0 \leq d \leq 1$)
  • $C(i)$ is the set of nodes that link to the $i^{th}$ node
  • $L(j)$ is the outdegree of the $j^{th}$ node
  • $N$ is the number of nodes (order)
